Na '''totolo ni rarama''' ena [[lala]], tukuna wasoma {{mvar|'''c'''}}, e na raraba [[vakayago tudei]] bibi ena vuqa na vanua ni [[fisiki]]. Its exact value is defined as {{val|299792458|u=metres per second}} (approximately {{cvt|300000|km/s|mi/s|comma=gaps|sigfig=3}}<ref group="Note" name="imperial" />). It is exact because by international agreement a [[Metre#Speed of light definition|metre]] is defined as the length of the path travelled by light in vacuum during a time interval of {{frac|1|{{val|299792458}}}} [[second]].{{refn|group="Note"|Which is in turn defined to be the length of time occupied by 9,192,631,770 cycles of the radiation emitted by a cesium-133 atom in a transition between two specified energy states.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://physics.nist.gov/cuu/Units/second.html|title=Base unit definitions: Second|website=physics.nist.gov|access-date=7 April 2018}}</ref>}}<ref name="penrose">{{Cite book|last=Penrose|first=R|year=2004|title=The Road to Reality: A Complete Guide to the Laws of the Universe|pages=410–11|publisher=Vintage Books|isbn=978-0-679-77631-4|quote=...{{nbsp}}the most accurate standard for the metre is conveniently ''defined'' so that there are exactly 299,792,458 of them to the distance travelled by light in a standard second, giving a value for the metre that very accurately matches the now inadequately precise standard metre rule in Paris.|title-link=The Road to Reality: A Complete Guide to the Laws of the Universe}}</ref> According to [[special relativity]], {{math|''c''}} is the upper limit for the speed at which conventional matter and [[Physical information|information]] can travel. Though this speed is most commonly associated with [[light]], it is also the speed at which all [[Massless particle|massless particles]] and [[Field (physics)|field]] perturbations travel in vacuum, including [[electromagnetic radiation]] and [[Gravitational wave|gravitational waves]]. Such particles and waves travel at {{math|''c''}} regardless of the motion of the source or the [[Inertial frame of reference|inertial reference frame]] of the observer. Particles with nonzero [[rest mass]] can approach {{mvar|c}}, but can never actually reach it. In the [[Theory of relativity|special and general theories of relativity]], {{math|''c''}} interrelates [[Spacetime|space and time]], and also appears in the famous equation of [[mass–energy equivalence]] {{math|1=''E'' = ''mc''<sup>2</sup>}}.<ref name="LeClerq">{{Cite book|last=Uzan|first=J-P|last2=Leclercq|first2=B|year=2008|title=The Natural Laws of the Universe: Understanding Fundamental Constants|url=https://books.google.com/?id=dSAWX8TNpScC&pg=PA43|pages=43–44|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-0-387-73454-5}}</ref>
